s]]\n* Date: 21\u201325 May\n\n{{6TeamRR-TennisWide\n| title-1=&nbsp;\n| title-2=RR<br />W\u2013L\n| title-3=Set<br />W\u2013L\n| title-4=Game<br />W\u2013L\n| title-5=Standings\n\n| seed-1=\n| team-1-abbrev={{flagu|TUN|1959}}\n| team-1='''{{davis|TUN|1959}}'''\n| match-w/l-1='''5\u20130'''\n| set-w/l-1='''{{nowrap|27\u20135 (84%)}}'''\n| game-w/l-1='''{{nowrap|177\u201385 (68%)}}'''\n| standings-1='''1'''\n\n| seed-2=\n| team-2-abbrev={{flagu|CYP}}\n| team-2='''{{davis|CYP}}'''\n| match-w/l-2='''4\u20131'''\n| set-w/l-2='''{{nowrap|23\u20138 (74%)}}'''\n| game-w/l-2='''{{nowrap|168\u2013109 (61%)}}'''\n| standings-2='''2'''\n\n| seed-3=\n| team-3-abbrev={{flagu|BEN}}\n| team-3={{davis|BEN}}\n| match-w/l-3=3\u20132\n| set-w/l-3={{nowrap|16\u201312 (57%)}}\n| game-w/l-3={{nowrap|133\u2013108 (55%)}}\n| standings-3=3\n\n| seed-4=\n| team-4-abbrev={{flagu|ZAM}}\n| team-4={{davis|ZAM}}\n| match-w/l-4=2\u20133\n| set-w/l-4={{nowrap|17\u201313 (57%)}}\n| game-w/l-4={{nowrap|146\u2013117 (56%)}}\n| standings-4=4\n\n| seed-5=\n| team-5-abbrev={{flagu|AZE}}\n| team-5={{davis|AZE}}\n| match-w/l-5=1\u20134\n| set-w/l-5={{nowrap|4\u201324 (14%)}}\n| game-w/l-5={{nowrap|65\u2013151 (30%)}}\n| standings-5=5\n\n| seed-6=\n| team-6-abbrev={{flagu|CGO}}\n| team-6={{davis|CGO}}\n| match-w/l-6=0\u20135\n| set-w/l-6={{nowrap|3\u201328 (10%)}}\n| game-w/l-6={{nowrap|55\u2013174 (24%)}}\n| standings-6=6\n\n|color-row-1=CCFFCC           |1v2=2\u20131 |1v3=3\u20130 |1v4=2\u20131 |1v5=3\u20130 |1v6=3\u20130\n|color-row-2=CCFFCC |2v1=1\u20132           |2v3=2\u20131 |2v4=2\u20131 |2v5=3\u20130 |2v6=3\u20130\n|color-row-3= |3v1=0\u20133 |3v2=1\u20132           |3v4=2\u20131 |3v5=3\u20130 |3v6=3\u20130\n|color-row-4= |4v1=1\u20132 |4v2=1\u20132 |4v3=1\u20132           |4v5=3\u20130 |4v6=3\u20130\n|color-row-5= |5v1=0\u20133 |5v2=0\u20133 |5v3=0\u20133 |5v4=0\u20133           |5v6=2\u20131\n|color-row-6= |6v1=0\u20133 |6v2=0\u20133 |6v3=0\u20133 |6v4=0\u20133 |6v5=1\u20132\n}}\n\n* {{davis|TUN|1959}} and {{davis|CYP}} promoted to Group III in 1998.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.daviscup.com Davis Cup official website]\n\n[[Category:Davis Cup Europe/Africa Zone]]\n[[Category:1997 Davis Cup|Europe/Africa Zone]]\n[[Category:1997 Davis Cup Europe/Africa Zone| ]]\n", "name_user": "Sims2aholic8", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997_Davis_Cup_Europe/Africa_Zone"}
{"title_page": "FV432", "text_new": "{{Infobox weapon\n|name=FV432\n|image=GKN-Sankey FV432 pic5.JPG\n|image_size= 300\n|caption=FV432 at the 2012 [[War and Peace Revival|War and Peace Show]]\n|origin= [[United Kingdom]]\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service= 1963&ndash;present\n|type=[[Armoured personnel carrier]]\n|manufacturer=[[GKN|GKN Sankey]]\n|is_vehicle=yes\n|is_UK=yes\n|length=5.25 m\n|width=2.8 m\n|height=2.28 m\n|weight=15 tons (15.3 t)\n|suspension=torsion-bar, 5 road wheels\n|speed= 44 mph (70 km/h)\n|vehicle_range=580 km\n|primary_armament=7.62 mm [[L7 (machine gun)|L7 GPMG]]\n|secondary_armament=smoke dischargers\n|armour=12.7 mm max\n|engine=[[Rolls-Royce Limited|Rolls-Royce]] K60 multi-fuel\n|crew=2 + 10 troops\n|engine_power=240 hp <!--( kW)-->\n|pw_ratio=15.7 hp/tonne\n}}\n\nThe '''FV432''' is the [[armoured personnel carrier]] variant of the [[British Army]]'s [[FV430 series]] of [[armoured fighting vehicle]]s. Since its introduction in the 1960s, it has been the most common variant, being used for transporting infantry on the battlefield. In the 1980s, almost 2,500 vehicles were in use, with around 1,500 now{{When|date=December 2018}} remaining in operation - mostly in supporting arms rather than front-line infantry service.\n\nAlthough the FV432 Series was to have been phased out of service in favour of newer vehicles, such as the [[Warrior Tracked Armoured Vehicle|Warrior]] and [[Combat Vehicle Reconnaissance (tracked)|the CVR(T) series]], 500 have been upgraded to extend their service into the next decade.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.defense-aerospace.com/article-view/release/67765/bae-wins-extra-funds-for-fv432-upgrade-%28mar-31%29.html|title=BAE Systems Awarded \u00a315 Million Contract to Support Upgraded FV432 Armoured Vehicle|last=|first=|date=30 March 2006|website=defence-aerospace.com|publisher=Briganti et Associ\u00e9s 19 Bld du Parc, 92200 Neuilly Sur Seine|access-date=24 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn light of the army's need for additional armoured vehicles in the Afghan and [[Iraq]]i theatres, the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] announced in August 2006 that an extra 70 vehicles would be upgraded by [[BAE Systems]] in addition to the 54 already ordered as part of their force protection initiative. The improvements take the form of an engine upgrade, a new steering unit and a new braking system, as well as improvement in armour protection to a level similar to that of the Warrior. In addition, plates lined with Kevlar have been added to the bottom hull. This is intended to provide better protection against improvised explosive devices. It is intended that these FV432s will free up the Warrior vehicles for provision of reserve firepower status and/or rotation out of theatre. The updated version is called the Bulldog.\n\nFV432s have been used to portray historical vehicles, and are often mocked up to resemble World War II or Cold War era military vehicles in film productions and TV series.\n\n==History==\nThe FV432 was designed to be the armoured personnel carrier in the FV430 series. Production started in 1962 by [[GKN Sankey]] and ended in 1971, after constructing approximately 3,000 vehicles.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n[[File:FV 432 APC of the 7th Brigade Royal Scots.JPEG|thumb|left|A FV432 in Kuwait during the [[Gulf War]]]]\n\nThe FV432 is of all-steel construction. The chassis is a conventional tracked design with the engine at the front and the driving position to the right. Directly behind the driver's position is the vehicle commander's hatch. There is a large round opening in the passenger compartment roof, which has a split/folding (concertina) hatch, and a (right hand) side-hinged door in the rear for loading and unloading. As in many designs of its era, there are no firing ports for the troops carried - British Army doctrine having been for troops to dismount from vehicles to fight, unlike Russian infantry fighting vehicles that largely incorporate ports. The passenger compartment has five seats on either side - these fold up to provide a flat cargo space.\n\nAn [[CBRN|NBC]] (nuclear, biological, and chemical weapons) system is fitted, normal ventilation provided by a fan mounted in the forward right hand side of the vehicle, air being drawn through a paper element filter (mounted externally on the right hand side of the hull), filtered air being distributed by a duct running around the perimeter of the interior at roof level, extending into the driver's compartment. Provision is made to add carbon filters in case of gas attack, and the system can accommodate heaters and/or air conditioning units. A roof-mounted relief valve allows a constant minimal pressure to be maintained and prevent ingress of foreign matter in the event of blast or alterations in external atmospheric pressure.\n\nWading screens and a trim vane were fitted as standard and an extension provided to elevate the exhaust pipe. The basic vehicle, which could be readied for wading in approximately five minutes, has a water speed of about 6&nbsp;km/h when converted for swimming and was propelled by its tracks.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=AFV Profile 53 The FV 432 Series|last=Foss|first=Christopher F.|publisher=Profile Publications Limited|year=1973|isbn=|location=Profile Publications Ltd, Coburg Hse, Sheet Street, Windsor, Berks|pages=9}}</ref> Most of these vehicles have had their amphibious capability removed.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\nFV432s in service with infantry battalions<!--The individual batalions of a multi-battalion regiment were often equipped for different roles, e.g. armoured (Warrior), mechanised (FV432 or SAXON), light roles (inc. air-portable &, for the guards, public duties)--> are equipped with a pintle-mounted [[L7 (machine gun)|L7 GPMG]] (if not fitted with the Peak Engineering turret). Vehicles with the Royal Artillery, Royal Engineers and Royal Signals were originally fitted with the L4A4 variant of the [[Bren light machine gun]], but they now use the GPMG. When equipped with the GPMG, the vehicle carries 1,600 rounds of belted 7.62mm ammunition; when carrying the Bren LMG, the vehicle carried 1,400 rounds of 7.62mm ammunition (50 magazines, each holding 28 rounds). There are two three-barrel smoke dischargers at the front.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\nThe [[Australian Army]] evaluated two pre-production FV432s during 1962 and 1963, but decided to [[M113 armoured personnel carriers in Australian service|purchase M113 amoured personnel carriers]] instead. The trials undertaken in [[Queensland]] demonstrated that the M113's performance was superior to that of the FV432.<ref>{{cite book |last=Cecil |first=Michael K.|editor1-last=Baines |editor1-first=John, RFD |editor2-last=Branagan |editor2-first=Peter, OAM |editor3-last=Finlayson |editor3-first=David |title=The AFV School: 70 years of training Australian armour |publisher=Royal Australian Armoured Corps |date=2011 |pages=48\u201350 |chapter=A Major Move to Mobility: Introduction of the M113A1 Family of Vehicles}}</ref>\n\nA number of surplus vehicles were sold to the [[Indian Army]] after being withdrawn from British service.\n\nMany FV432s are privately owned in the UK due to the relatively low price for which they can be bought.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\n==Variants==\n[[File:FV432 interior.JPG|thumb|right|The interior of an FV432]]\nThe FV432 has been produced in three major variants, the Mark 1 (with a Mark 1/1 minor variant) with [[petrol]] engines, the Mark 2 with a [[Rolls-Royce K60]] multi-fuel engine and the Mark 3 with a diesel engine. The Mark 2 minor variant, the 2/1, has its NBC pack flush with the hull side. An uparmoured variant, for use in Iraq and Afghanistan, of the Mark 3 was known as Bulldog. This name now appears to be extended to all Mark 3 versions of the FV432.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\nThe FV432 has proven to be flexible in use and can be converted from one role to another with reasonable ease using 'installation kits' (IK), or more permanently with minor modifications to the hull. Major or more significant modifications have usually led to a new FV43n number. In addition to the normal [[armoured personnel carrier]] role, it has been used as:\n*a command vehicle, with seven crew, two mapboards and extra communications equipment (with an additional canvas \"penthouse\")\n*an ambulance, with spots for up to four stretchers or two stretcher and five seated patients but would not carry any armament other than the smoke dischargers.\n*a cargo carrier, for up to 3,600&nbsp;kg\n*a communications vehicle\n*a recovery vehicle. Designated as the FV434, it includes a rear cutout to a \"pickup-truck\" box to carry a spare engine/other stores with tool store below, an internally mounted winch, and a 2.5-tonne lift arm.<ref name=\":1\" /> Frequently equipped with the canvas \"penthouse\".{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\nFV432s used by combat infantry units have also been equipped with:<ref name=\":1\" />\n*[[L6 Wombat|WOMBAT recoilless rifle]] early models carried this armament internally, using ramps and a hand winch to deploy and recover the weapon. Later models mounted it externally above the rear hatch. In this arrangement the weapon had limited-traverse (30\u00b0 lateral, +7.5\u00b0 \u22123\u00b0 elevation), but it could also be demounted as in the earlier arrangement. \n*[[Carl Gustav recoilless rifle|84mm Carl Gustav recoilless rifle]] mounted on a bar across the top of the troop compartment.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n*[[L16 81mm Mortar|81mm mortar]] on a turntable in the rear of the hull can be traversed through 360\u00b0 firing through the roof hatch; 160 mortar bombs are carried; crew consists of a driver, commander and four men\n*Peak Engineering turret with the L37A1 variant of the [[L7 (machine gun)|7.62mm GPMG]], replacing the roof hatch.\n*[[RARDEN|30 mm RARDEN]]-gun equipped turret (taken from the [[Fox Armoured Reconnaissance Vehicle|Fox scout car]]; 13 converted). These were used by the [[Berlin Infantry Brigade|Berlin Brigade]] (usually in the [[Berlin camouflage|distinctive urban camouflage]] used there).<ref>{{Cite web\n  |title=FV432 - 30mm RARDEN MK (UK)\n  |website=PanzerBaer.de\n  |url=http://www.panzerbaer.de/types/uk_fv432_rarden.htm\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web\n  |title=FV432 Rarden, Dickensweg, Berlin 1980s\n  |author=Torfaen Corvine\n  |date=20 February 2016\n  |website=Flickr\n  |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/16498755@N07/25119592716\n}}</ref> One of these, of the [[Royal Hampshires]], was driven by their [[royal colonel|honorary colonel]], [[Diana, Princess of Wales]], on her visit to Berlin in 1985<ref>{{Cite web\n  |title=Some notes on the British Berlin Brigade of 1985\n  |website=Sparker's Wargaming Blog\n  |date=17 November 2015\n  |url=http://sparkerswargames.blogspot.co.uk/2015/11/some-notes-on-british-berlin-brigade-of.html\n}}</ref> These were later bought by the tank driving and paint-balling company Armourgeddon (who also converted more). These have been modified with a compressed air cylinder on the rear of the turret for the paintball gun.\n*[[ZB 298]] Elliott Automation Grounds Surveillance Radar\n*[[MILAN]] anti-tank missiles (two missile teams (deployed away from the vehicle)\n\nFV432s used by the [[Royal Artillery]] have been equipped with:<ref name=\":1\" />\n*a battery command post with FACE fire control computer\n*a battery command post with BATES battlefield artillery target engagement system\n[[File:20050626-006-FV-432.jpg|right|thumb|A privately owned FV432 in a carnival procession.]]\n*[[Cymbeline (radar)|Cymbeline]] mortar-locating radar\n*sound ranging equipment\n*observation post vehicle with [[ZB 298]] [[Elliott Brothers (computer company)|Elliott Automation]] Grounds Surveillance Radar\n\nFV432s used by the [[Royal Engineers]] have been equipped with:<ref name=\":1\" />\n*a towed layer for [[L9 Bar Mine|L9 anti-tank Bar Mine]]\n*a launcher for [[L10 Ranger Anti-Personnel Mine]]\n*a towed [[Giant Viper]] mine-clearing system\n*a [[Thales Group]] [[SWARM]] [[Remote Weapon System]]\n\n===British Army designations===\nFV431 Armoured load carrier \u2013 one prototype produced; the [[Alvis Stalwart]] 6\u00d76 vehicle was selected instead for the load carrier role\n*FV432 Armoured Personnel Carrier\n*[[FV433 Abbot SPG|FV433 Field Artillery, Self-Propelled \"Abbot\"]] \u2013 105&nbsp;mm self-propelled gun built by Vickers\n*[[FV434]] \"Carrier, Maintenance, Full Tracked\" \u2013 REME Maintenance carrier with a crew of four and a hydraulically driven crane with a lifting capacity of {{convert|3,050|kg|LT|abbr=on}}\n*FV435 Wavell - communications vehicle\n*FV436 Command and control \u2013 some fitted with [[Green Archer (radar)|Green Archer]] [[counter-battery radar]], later [[Cymbeline (radar)|Cymbeline radar]]\n*FV437 Pathfinder vehicle \u2013 based on an FV432 with integral buoyancy and other waterjets \u2013 prototype only\n*[[FV438 Swingfire]] \u2013 guided missile launcher for [[Swingfire]] anti-tank missile\n*FV439 Signals vehicle \u2013 many variants\n\n===Bulldog===\n{{main|FV430 series}}\n[[File:The first delivery of the upgraded FV430 Mk3 Bulldog vehicles MOD 45147090.jpg|thumb|A FV430 Mk3 Bulldog in Iraq during 2007]]\nThe need to upgrade the FV432 to extend its service life further led the MoD to sign an \u00a385m contract with [[BAE Systems Land Systems]] to update over 1,000 FV 432s to Mark 3 standard. Major changes include a new diesel engine and braking system. Initially, only FV432 and 434 models were converted, but other variants are being considered. The first 500 of the batch were handed over to the British Army in December 2006.<ref name=\":0\" /> For service in Iraq and Afghanistan, air-conditioning, enhanced [[reactive armour]] and IED jammers have been added. Initially, only these further enhanced versions were known by the name Bulldog; but the term now appears to be applied to all Mark 3 vehicles.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|War}}\n*[[M113 armored personnel carrier|M113]] \u2013 similar US-built armoured personnel carrier\n*[[MT-LB]]\n*[[BTR-50]]\n*[[List of FV series military vehicles]]\n*[[MLVM]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Howard, Les \"Winter Warriors - Across Bosnia with the PBI\", {{ISBN|978-1-84624-077-5}} Critical account of a British army Peacekeeper operating from FV 432s at the end of the Bosnian civil war\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|FV432}}\n\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110428093400/http://www.sloppyjalopy.com/fv432.htm Sloppy Jalopy]\n*[http://www.armedforces.co.uk/army/listings/l0035.html Armedforces.co.uk]\n\n{{GKN}}{{ModernUKAFVsNav | style= wide}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fv432}}\n[[Category:Amphibious armoured personnel carriers]]\n[[Category:Armoured personnel carriers of the Cold War]]\n[[Category:Armoured personnel carriers of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Tracked infantry fighting vehicles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox weapon\n|name=FV432\n|image=GKN-Sankey FV432 pic5.JPG\n|image_size= 300\n|caption=FV432 at the 2012 [[War and Peace Revival|War and Peace Show]]\n|origin= [[United Kingdom]]\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service= 1963&ndash;present\n|type=[[Armoured personnel carrier]]\n|manufacturer=[[GKN|GKN Sankey]]\n|is_vehicle=yes\n|is_UK=yes\n|length=5.25 m\n|width=2.8 m\n|height=2.28 m\n|weight=15 tons (15.3 t)\n|suspension=torsion-bar, 5 road wheels\n|speed= 44 mph (70 km/h)\n|vehicle_range=580 km\n|primary_armament=7.62 mm [[L7 (machine gun)|L7 GPMG]]\n|secondary_armament=smoke dischargers\n|armour=12.7 mm max\n|engine=[[Rolls-Royce Limited|Rolls-Royce]] K60 multi-fuel\n|crew=2 + 10 troops\n|engine_power=240 hp <!--( kW)-->\n|pw_ratio=15.7 hp/tonne\n}}\n\nThe '''FV432''' is the [[armoured personnel carrier]] variant of the [[British Army]]'s [[FV430 series]] of [[armoured fighting vehicle]]s. Since its introduction in the 1960s, it has been the most common variant, being used for transporting infantry on the battlefield. In the 1980s, almost 2,500 vehicles were in use, with around 1,500 now{{When|date=December 2018}} remaining in operation - mostly in supporting arms rather than front-line infantry service.\n\nAlthough the FV432 Series was to have been phased out of service in favour of newer vehicles, such as the [[Warrior Tracked Armoured Vehicle|Warrior]] and [[Combat Vehicle Reconnaissance (tracked)|the CVR(T) series]], 500 have been upgraded to extend their service into the next decade.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.defense-aerospace.com/article-view/release/67765/bae-wins-extra-funds-for-fv432-upgrade-%28mar-31%29.html|title=BAE Systems Awarded \u00a315 Million Contract to Support Upgraded FV432 Armoured Vehicle|last=|first=|date=30 March 2006|website=defence-aerospace.com|publisher=Briganti et Associ\u00e9s 19 Bld du Parc, 92200 Neuilly Sur Seine|access-date=24 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn light of the army's need for additional armoured vehicles in the Afghan and [[Iraq]]i theatres, the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] announced in August 2006 that an extra 70 vehicles would be upgraded by [[BAE Systems]] in addition to the 54 already ordered as part of their force protection initiative. The improvements take the form of an engine upgrade, a new steering unit and a new braking system, as well as improvement in armour protection to a level similar to that of the Warrior. In addition, plates lined with Kevlar have been added to the bottom hull. This is intended to provide better protection against improvised explosive devices. It is intended that these FV432s will free up the Warrior vehicles for provision of reserve firepower status and/or rotation out of theatre. The updated version is called the Bulldog.\n\nFV432s have been used to portray historical vehicles, and are often mocked up to resemble World War II or Cold War era military vehicles in film productions and TV series.\n\n==History==\nThe FV432 was designed to be the armoured personnel carrier in the FV430 series. Production started in 1962 by [[GKN Sankey]] and ended in 1971, after constructing approximately 3,000 vehicles.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n[[File:FV 432 APC of the 7th Brigade Royal Scots.JPEG|thumb|left|A FV432 in Kuwait during the [[Gulf War]]]]\n\nThe FV432 is of all-steel construction. The chassis is a conventional tracked design with the engine at the front and the driving position to the right. Directly behind the driver's position is the vehicle commander's hatch. There is a large round opening in the passenger compartment roof, which has a split/folding (concertina) hatch, and a (right hand) side-hinged door in the rear for loading and unloading. As in many designs of its era, there are no firing ports for the troops carried - British Army doctrine having been for troops to dismount from vehicles to fight, unlike Russian infantry fighting vehicles that largely incorporate ports. The passenger compartment has five seats on either side - these fold up to provide a flat cargo space.\n\nAn [[CBRN|NBC]] (nuclear, biological, and chemical weapons) system is fitted, normal ventilation provided by a fan mounted in the forward right hand side of the vehicle, air being drawn through a paper element filter (mounted externally on the right hand side of the hull), filtered air being distributed by a duct running around the perimeter of the interior at roof level, extending into the driver's compartment. Provision is made to add carbon filters in case of gas attack, and the system can accommodate heaters and/or air conditioning units. A roof-mounted relief valve allows a constant minimal pressure to be maintained and prevent ingress of foreign matter in the event of blast or alterations in external atmospheric pressure.\n\nWading screens and a trim vane were fitted as standard and an extension provided to elevate the exhaust pipe. The basic vehicle, which could be readied for wading in approximately five minutes, has a water speed of about 6&nbsp;km/h when converted for swimming and was propelled by its tracks.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=AFV Profile 53 The FV 432 Series|last=Foss|first=Christopher F.|publisher=Profile Publications Limited|year=1973|isbn=|location=Profile Publications Ltd, Coburg Hse, Sheet Street, Windsor, Berks|pages=9}}</ref> Most of these vehicles have had their amphibious capability removed.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\nFV432s in service with infantry battalions<!--The individual batalions of a multi-battalion regiment were often equipped for different roles, e.g. armoured (Warrior), mechanised (FV432 or SAXON), light roles (inc. air-portable &, for the guards, public duties)--> are equipped with a pintle-mounted [[L7 (machine gun)|L7 GPMG]] (if not fitted with the Peak Engineering turret). Vehicles with the Royal Artillery, Royal Engineers and Royal Signals were originally fitted with the L4A4 variant of the [[Bren light machine gun]], but they now use the GPMG. When equipped with the GPMG, the vehicle carries 1,600 rounds of belted 7.62mm ammunition; when carrying the Bren LMG, the vehicle carried 1,400 rounds of 7.62mm ammunition (50 magazines, each holding 28 rounds). There are two three-barrel smoke dischargers at the front.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\nThe [[Australian Army]] evaluated two pre-production FV432s during 1962 and 1963, but decided to [[M113 armoured personnel carriers in Australian service|purchase M113 amoured personnel carriers]] instead. The trials undertaken in [[Queensland]] demonstrated that the M113's performance was superior to that of the FV432.<ref>{{cite book |last=Cecil |first=Michael K.|editor1-last=Baines |editor1-first=John, RFD |editor2-last=Branagan |editor2-first=Peter, OAM |editor3-last=Finlayson |editor3-first=David |title=The AFV School: 70 years of training Australian armour |publisher=Royal Australian Armoured Corps |date=2011 |pages=48\u201350 |chapter=A Major Move to Mobility: Introduction of the M113A1 Family of Vehicles}}</ref>\n\nA number of surplus vehicles were sold to the [[Indian Army]] after being withdrawn from British service.\n\nMany FV432s are privately owned in the UK due to the relatively low price for which they can be bought.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\n==Variants==\n[[File:FV432 interior.JPG|thumb|right|The interior of an FV432]]\nThe FV432 has been produced in three major variants, the Mark 1 (with a Mark 1/1 minor variant) with [[petrol]] engines, the Mark 2 with a [[Rolls-Royce K60]] multi-fuel engine and the Mark 3 with a diesel engine. The Mark 2 minor variant, the 2/1, has its NBC pack flush with the hull side. An uparmoured variant, for use in Iraq and Afghanistan, of the Mark 3 was known as Bulldog. This name now appears to be extended to all Mark 3 versions of the FV432.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\nThe FV432 has proven to be flexible in use and can be converted from one role to another with reasonable ease using 'installation kits' (IK), or more permanently with minor modifications to the hull. Major or more significant modifications have usually led to a new FV43n number. In addition to the normal [[armoured personnel carrier]] role, it has been used as:\n*a command vehicle, with seven crew, two mapboards and extra communications equipment (with an additional canvas \"penthouse\")\n*an ambulance, with spots for up to four stretchers or two stretcher and five seated patients but would not carry any armament other than the smoke dischargers.\n*a cargo carrier, for up to 3,600&nbsp;kg\n*a communications vehicle\n*a recovery vehicle. Designated as the FV434, it includes a rear cutout to a \"pickup-truck\" box to carry a spare engine/other stores with tool store below, an internally mounted winch, and a 2.5-tonne lift arm.<ref name=\":1\" /> Frequently equipped with the canvas \"penthouse\".{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\nFV432s used by combat infantry units have also been equipped with:<ref name=\":1\" />\n*[[L6 Wombat|WOMBAT recoilless rifle]] early models carried this armament internally, using ramps and a hand winch to deploy and recover the weapon. Later models mounted it externally above the rear hatch. In this arrangement the weapon had limited-traverse (30\u00b0 lateral, +7.5\u00b0 \u22123\u00b0 elevation), but it could also be demounted as in the earlier arrangement. \n*[[Carl Gustav recoilless rifle|84mm Carl Gustav recoilless rifle]] mounted on a bar across the top of the troop compartment.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n*[[L16 81mm Mortar|81mm mortar]] on a turntable in the rear of the hull can be traversed through 360\u00b0 firing through the roof hatch; 160 mortar bombs are carried; crew consists of a driver, commander and four men\n*Peak Engineering turret with the L37A1 variant of the [[L7 (machine gun)|7.62mm GPMG]], replacing the roof hatch.\n*[[RARDEN|30 mm RARDEN]]-gun equipped turret (taken from the [[Fox Armoured Reconnaissance Vehicle|Fox scout car]]; 13 converted). These were used by the [[Berlin Infantry Brigade|Berlin Brigade]] (usually in the [[Berlin camouflage|distinctive urban camouflage]] used there).<ref>{{Cite web\n  |title=FV432 - 30mm RARDEN MK (UK)\n  |website=PanzerBaer.de\n  |url=http://www.panzerbaer.de/types/uk_fv432_rarden.htm\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web\n  |title=FV432 Rarden, Dickensweg, Berlin 1980s\n  |author=Torfaen Corvine\n  |date=20 February 2016\n  |website=Flickr\n  |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/16498755@N07/25119592716\n}}</ref> One of these, of the [[Royal Hampshires]], was driven by their [[royal colonel|honorary colonel]], [[Diana, Princess of Wales]], on her visit to Berlin in 1985<ref>{{Cite web\n  |title=Some notes on the British Berlin Brigade of 1985\n  |website=Sparker's Wargaming Blog\n  |date=17 November 2015\n  |url=http://sparkerswargames.blogspot.co.uk/2015/11/some-notes-on-british-berlin-brigade-of.html\n}}</ref> These were later bought by the tank driving and paint-balling company Armourgeddon (who also converted more). These have been modified with a compressed air cylinder on the rear of the turret for the paintball gun.\n*[[ZB 298]] Elliott Automation Grounds Surveillance Radar\n*[[MILAN]] anti-tank missiles (two missile teams (deployed away from the vehicle)\n\nFV432s used by the [[Royal Artillery]] have been equipped with:<ref name=\":1\" />\n*a battery command post with FACE fire control computer\n*a battery command post with BATES battlefield artillery target engagement system\n[[File:20050626-006-FV-432.jpg|right|thumb|A privately owned FV432 in a carnival procession.]]\n*[[Cymbeline (radar)|Cymbeline]] mortar-locating radar\n*sound ranging equipment\n*observation post vehicle with [[ZB 298]] [[Elliott Brothers (computer company)|Elliott Automation]] Grounds Surveillance Radar\n\nFV432s used by the [[Royal Engineers]] have been equipped with:<ref name=\":1\" />\n*a towed layer for [[L9 Bar Mine|L9 anti-tank Bar Mine]]\n*a launcher for [[L10 Ranger Anti-Personnel Mine]]\n*a towed [[Giant Viper]] mine-clearing system\n*a [[Thales Group]] [[SWARM]] [[Remote Weapon System]]\n\n===British Army designations===\nFV431 Armoured load carrier \u2013 one prototype produced; the [[Alvis Stalwart]] 6\u00d76 vehicle was selected instead for the load carrier role\n*FV432 Armoured Personnel Carrier\n*[[FV433 Abbot SPG|FV433 Field Artillery, Self-Propelled \"Abbot\"]] \u2013 105&nbsp;mm self-propelled gun built by Vickers\n*[[FV434]] \"Carrier, Maintenance, Full Tracked\" \u2013 REME Maintenance carrier with a crew of four and a hydraulically driven crane with a lifting capacity of {{convert|3,050|kg|LT|abbr=on}}\n*FV435 Wavell - communications vehicle\n*FV436 Command and control \u2013 some fitted with [[Green Archer (radar)[Green Archer]] [[counter-battery radar]], later [[Cymbeline (radar)|Cymbeline radar]]\n*FV437 Pathfinder vehicle \u2013 based on an FV432 with integral buoyancy and other waterjets \u2013 prototype only\n*[[FV438 Swingfire]] \u2013 guided missile launcher for [[Swingfire]] anti-tank missile\n*FV439 Signals vehicle \u2013 many variants\n\n===Bulldog===\n{{main|FV430 series}}\n[[File:The first delivery of the upgraded FV430 Mk3 Bulldog vehicles MOD 45147090.jpg|thumb|A FV430 Mk3 Bulldog in Iraq during 2007]]\nThe need to upgrade the FV432 to extend its service life further led the MoD to sign an \u00a385m contract with [[BAE Systems Land Systems]] to update over 1,000 FV 432s to Mark 3 standard. Major changes include a new diesel engine and braking system. Initially, only FV432 and 434 models were converted, but other variants are being considered. The first 500 of the batch were handed over to the British Army in December 2006.<ref name=\":0\" /> For service in Iraq and Afghanistan, air-conditioning, enhanced [[reactive armour]] and IED jammers have been added. Initially, only these further enhanced versions were known by the name Bulldog; but the term now appears to be applied to all Mark 3 vehicles.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|War}}\n*[[M113 armored personnel carrier|M113]] \u2013 similar US-built armoured personnel carrier\n*[[MT-LB]]\n*[[BTR-50]]\n*[[List of FV series military vehicles]]\n*[[MLVM]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Howard, Les \"Winter Warriors - Across Bosnia with the PBI\", {{ISBN|978-1-84624-077-5}} Critical account of a British army Peacekeeper operating from FV 432s at the end of the Bosnian civil war\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|FV432}}\n\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110428093400/http://www.sloppyjalopy.com/fv432.htm Sloppy Jalopy]\n*[http://www.armedforces.co.uk/army/listings/l0035.html Armedforces.co.uk]\n\n{{GKN}}{{ModernUKAFVsNav | style= wide}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n